history.content:
P/NP has practically no effect on tech companies -- they hardly ever look at your transcript for internships/first full-time.

If you're planning for graduate school then it's generally advised not to P/NP technical courses. That being said, if you expect CS 161 to be unrelated to your future endeavors then it's better to put your focus elsewhere and P/NP the class.

In any case, seek multiple opinions on this matter.

I'm thinking of pass/no passing CS 161. It seems like an important class to take, so I don't want to drop it. But I don't like the material and I don't think I'll end up doing well in the class as a result. 

Will it look bad to tech companies (for SWE roles) if I P/NP it? Does P/NP-ing technical courses look bad in general?
history.subject: Pass/No Pass CS Classes
